“That is why the Men’s Club is there to fulfil this need in a safe, sophisticated and conducive environment.” Never one to shy away from a challenge, Razafy is using the social enterprise to marshal the youth, but also raises questions about life’s unfolding, saying away we observe cycles – about generations, history and struggle, and say nothing.

“What life and history have taught us is to observe and understand the old adage that old is gold. The world has taught us a lesson; it is time for us to understand.”

Lack of paradigm is deemed historical as what is acceptable today might not have been acceptable yesterday or two decades ago. “As youth group in Seychelles crafting societal laudable changes you will always face the now and not tomorrow objections and not see eye to eye with your elders,” says Razafy, who strongly asserts that there is a role to be played and that niche must be responded to.

“There remains a significant portion in our community who still believe that I am young, I will plant yam[ vegetables] tomorrow, why do I care about the challenges of getting access, driving, shaving, making key decisions, and so on.”
